hook.real_world_problem:
In a large codebase you need data access for users, products, and orders. Without generic interfaces, you write three separate DAOs:

```java
class UserDao    { User findById(int id)    { ... } void save(User u)    { ... } }
class ProductDao { Product findById(int id) { ... } void save(Product p) { ... } }
class OrderDao   { Order findById(int id)   { ... } void save(Order o)   { ... } }
```

Three classes, all doing the same thing — find by ID, save — just for different types. This is the exact code duplication generics were designed to eliminate.

**With a generic interface:**

```java
interface Repository<T, ID> {
    Optional<T> findById(ID id);
    List<T> findAll();
    T save(T entity);
    void deleteById(ID id);
}

// One contract, three implementations:
class UserRepository    implements Repository<User, Integer>    { ... }
class ProductRepository implements Repository<Product, String>  { ... }
class OrderRepository   implements Repository<Order, Long>      { ... }
```

Every caller works with the interface — not the concrete class. Tests mock it. Different implementations (in-memory, database, cache) are swappable. And the code says EXACTLY what it does: 'this is a repository for T entities identified by ID'.

**This is Spring Data.** When you write `interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Integer>`, you're implementing a generic interface. Today you learn how to build those interfaces yourself.

concept_explanation.generic_interface_syntax:
**Generic interface syntax:**

```java
// Define: type parameter(s) after interface name
public interface Container<T> {
    void put(T item);
    T get();
    boolean isEmpty();
}

// With bounds:
public interface Sortable<T extends Comparable<T>> {
    void add(T item);
    T min();
    T max();
    List<T> sorted();
}

// Multiple type parameters:
public interface Converter<S, T> {
    T convert(S source);
}

// Default method — generic interface can have implementations:
public interface Repository<T, ID> {
    Optional<T> findById(ID id);
    List<T> findAll();
    T save(T entity);
    void deleteById(ID id);

    default boolean exists(ID id) {  // default = concrete implementation
        return findById(id).isPresent();
    }
}
```

concept_explanation.implementing_generic_interfaces:
**Three ways to implement a generic interface:**

```java
// 1. Provide concrete types — most common
class UserRepository implements Repository<User, Integer> {
    private Map<Integer, User> store = new HashMap<>();

    @Override
    public Optional<User> findById(Integer id) {
        return Optional.ofNullable(store.get(id));
    }

    @Override
    public List<User> findAll() { return new ArrayList<>(store.values()); }

    @Override
    public User save(User user) { store.put(user.getId(), user); return user; }

    @Override
    public void deleteById(Integer id) { store.remove(id); }
}

// 2. Keep generic — propagate the type parameter
class InMemoryRepository<T, ID> implements Repository<T, ID> {
    private Map<ID, T> store = new HashMap<>();
    // ... all methods stay generic with T and ID
}

// 3. Partially concrete
class IntKeyRepository<T> implements Repository<T, Integer> {
    // T still generic, ID fixed to Integer
}
```

concept_explanation.repository_pattern:
**Repository pattern** — generic CRUD data access:

```java
public interface Repository<T, ID> {
    Optional<T> findById(ID id);
    List<T> findAll();
    T save(T entity);                    // create or update
    void delete(T entity);
    long count();

    default boolean exists(ID id) {
        return findById(id).isPresent();
    }

    default List<T> saveAll(List<T> entities) {
        return entities.stream().map(this::save).collect(Collectors.toList());
    }
}

// Concrete implementation:
class UserRepository implements Repository<User, Integer> {
    private Map<Integer, User> store = new HashMap<>();
    private int nextId = 1;

    @Override
    public Optional<User> findById(Integer id) {
        return Optional.ofNullable(store.get(id));
    }

    @Override
    public User save(User user) {
        if (user.getId() == 0) user.setId(nextId++);
        store.put(user.getId(), user);
        return user;
    }

    // ... other methods

    // Domain-specific query:
    public Optional<User> findByEmail(String email) {
        return store.values().stream()
            .filter(u -> u.getEmail().equals(email))
            .findFirst();
    }
}

// This IS what Spring Data does — you just declare:
// interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Integer> {}
// and Spring generates the implementation.
```

concept_explanation.mapper_pattern:
**Mapper pattern** — bidirectional type conversion:

```java
public interface Mapper<S, T> {
    T mapTo(S source);
    S mapFrom(T target);

    // Default: convert a list
    default List<T> mapAllTo(List<S> sources) {
        return sources.stream().map(this::mapTo).collect(Collectors.toList());
    }
}

// Domain classes:
class User  { int id; String name; String email; ... }
class UserDto { String name; String email; ... }  // no ID — safe for APIs

// Mapper implementation:
class UserMapper implements Mapper<User, UserDto> {
    @Override
    public UserDto mapTo(User user) {
        UserDto dto = new UserDto();
        dto.setName(user.getName());
        dto.setEmail(user.getEmail());
        return dto;
    }

    @Override
    public User mapFrom(UserDto dto) {
        User user = new User();
        user.setName(dto.getName());
        user.setEmail(dto.getEmail());
        return user;
    }
}

// Usage:
UserMapper mapper = new UserMapper();
UserDto dto = mapper.mapTo(user);     // User → UserDto
User fromDto = mapper.mapFrom(dto);   // UserDto → User
List<UserDto> dtos = mapper.mapAllTo(users);  // default method
```

This is what MapStruct (Java's most popular mapping library) does — but MapStruct generates the implementations at compile time.

concept_explanation.strategy_pattern:
**Strategy pattern** — generic interchangeable algorithm:

```java
public interface SortStrategy<T> {
    void sort(List<T> list);
    String name();
}

// Implementations — each is an algorithm:
class BubbleSort<T extends Comparable<T>> implements SortStrategy<T> {
    @Override
    public void sort(List<T> list) {
        int n = list.size();
        for (int i = 0; i < n-1; i++)
            for (int j = 0; j < n-i-1; j++)
                if (list.get(j).compareTo(list.get(j+1)) > 0) {
                    T temp = list.get(j);
                    list.set(j, list.get(j+1));
                    list.set(j+1, temp);
                }
    }
    @Override public String name() { return "BubbleSort"; }
}

class NaturalSort<T extends Comparable<T>> implements SortStrategy<T> {
    @Override
    public void sort(List<T> list) { Collections.sort(list); }
    @Override public String name() { return "NaturalSort"; }
}

// Context:
class Sorter<T extends Comparable<T>> {
    private SortStrategy<T> strategy;

    Sorter(SortStrategy<T> strategy) { this.strategy = strategy; }

    void setStrategy(SortStrategy<T> strategy) { this.strategy = strategy; }

    void sort(List<T> list) {
        long start = System.nanoTime();
        strategy.sort(list);
        System.out.printf("%s: %dms%n", strategy.name(),
            (System.nanoTime() - start) / 1_000_000);
    }
}
```

concept_explanation.builder_pattern:
**Builder pattern** — generic fluent construction:

```java
public interface Builder<T> {
    T build();  // produce the final object
}

// Email builder:
class EmailBuilder implements Builder<Email> {
    private String to, subject, body;
    private List<String> cc = new ArrayList<>();

    EmailBuilder to(String to)         { this.to = to; return this; }
    EmailBuilder subject(String sub)    { this.subject = sub; return this; }
    EmailBuilder body(String body)      { this.body = body; return this; }
    EmailBuilder cc(String... addrs)    { cc.addAll(Arrays.asList(addrs)); return this; }

    @Override
    public Email build() {
        Objects.requireNonNull(to, "'to' is required");
        Objects.requireNonNull(subject, "'subject' is required");
        return new Email(to, subject, body != null ? body : "", cc);
    }
}

// Usage:
Email email = new EmailBuilder()
    .to("aisha@example.com")
    .subject("Welcome!")
    .body("Hello Aisha...")
    .cc("admin@example.com")
    .build();
```

Generic Builder<T> interface provides the contract; each builder class provides the fluent steps specific to T.

concept_explanation.combining_all_concepts:
**Putting it all together — a complete generic layer:**

```java
// 1. Generic interface (Repository)
interface Repository<T, ID> { ... }

// 2. Generic interface with bound (Sortable)
interface Sortable<T extends Comparable<T>> { List<T> sorted(); }

// 3. Implementation with two type params
class UserRepo implements Repository<User, Integer>, Sortable<User> { ... }

// 4. Factory method returning generic interface
<T, ID> Repository<T, ID> createRepo() { return new InMemoryRepository<>(); }

// 5. Method taking generic interface
void process(Repository<?, ?> repo) { System.out.println(repo.count()); }
```

This is the architecture of Spring's JpaRepository hierarchy — generic interfaces stacked together, each adding one capability.

